example.p:
Using the data in we can determine the formula for R(t), the number of atoms that remain radioactive after t years; choosing two ordered pairs and assuming that R(t)=a\ b^t
8000 & = ab^0 4000 & =ab^{5730}
This clearly means that a=8000, and
\frac{1}{2} & = b^{5730} \Longrightarrow b = \left( \frac{1}{2} \right)^{\frac{1}{5730}}
We can therefore say that
R(t)=8000\left(\frac12\right)^{\frac1{5730}t}
We can now determine how many atoms remain radioactive after 100 years
R(100)\approx 7904
Approximately 7904 atoms remain radioactive after 100 years.

How long it would take until there are only 6000 radioactive atoms remaining? We need to solve the equation
6000=8000\left( \frac{1}{2} \right)^{\frac{t}{5730}}
Using a graphing calculator, we obtain t\approx 2378. We conclude that 6000 radioactive atoms remain after approximately 2378 years.

statement.p:
Fredo didn't actually earn 12 interest after one year on his initial investment, 
so the 12 is in name only, and is called the {\em nominal} 
interest rate.

definition.statement:
       The compound interest formula is

         A(t) = P_0\left(1+\frac{r}{n}\right)^{nt}

       where:


P_0 is the initial amount invested;

r is the nominal interest rate;

n is the compounding frequency (see );

t is the amount of time that has passed since the initial investment (in years);

A(t) is the account balance (in dollars).

solution.p:
We will use our answer from :  f(t) \approx 95(0.936)^t where t is years since 1963. \\



